TITLE: Using QUnit assert.ok() to Test Truthy Values in JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: This example demonstrates how to use QUnit's assert.ok() function to test various values for truthiness. It shows both passing assertions with truthy values and failing assertions with falsy values.
SOURCE: https://github.com/qunitjs/qunit/blob/main/docs/api/assert/ok.md#2025-04-12_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
QUnit.test('example', function (assert) {
  // success
  assert.ok(true, 'boolean true');
  assert.ok('foo', 'non-empty string');
  assert.ok(1, 'number one');

  // failure
  assert.ok(false, 'boolean false');
  assert.ok('', 'empty string');
  assert.ok(0, 'number zero');
  assert.ok(NaN, 'NaN value');
  assert.ok(null, 'null value');
  assert.ok(undefined, 'undefined value');
});
```

